ngs><font color=#FFFFFF>Author</font></td><td valign=top background=http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/images/bar.jpg class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 30<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/18/02 4:34:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=87.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: to the king or queen?</span><hr size=1> &gt; If you were in charge of the nuclear ship<br>
&gt;presentation, to the king or queen, what would<br>
&gt;be your reasoning and what could you bring back<br>
&gt;to further the power of your financeer?<br>
<br>
 First, I'd prefer to go to the people, rather than a greedy ruler. Further, I wouldn't go to them as a petitioner to congress, asking for public money to do it. I'd go to the people saying something like &quot;where would you like to see our generation listed in the history books? As losers who fought endless wars over oil?&quot;<br>
 Push for something like what the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.marssociety.org/about/founding_declaration.asp">Mars Society</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> is trying to do, and do it entirely privately, with support for the adventure, the science, and the future.<br>
 Sure, lots of money is needed. I'd get some from advertizing rights for the companies whoi build the hardware, some from the astronauts doing promos if they want, more from companies investing in a consortium which handles the profit from the mission, intending to use the profit for furthering exploration and exploitation &amp; settlement of space (make the misions make money, so it pays for itself, intead of being a drain on investors).<br>
 Some good ideas on profitability here: &quot;a  <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://permanent.com/m-1stmis.htm">near-term first mission</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> and how it would be profitable&quot;<br>
<br>
 As for the inspiration, it can't be said any better than this (though it's been said many times, by other people, this is a good example):<br>
The Space Frontier Foundation's &quot;<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.space-frontier.org/POLICIES/Manifesto.html">Manifesto</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> for the Frontier&quot;.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 701<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/18/02 6:37:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=87.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: to the king or queen?</span><hr size=1> If it was a ruler then I'd simply point out the riches abundant in Asteroids. Most of the wealth on Earth in the form of heavier elements(gold, silver, berrylium, platinum, uranium etc) sank to the Earth's core long ago when the Planet was forming. Asteroids are completely different. Low mass so low gravity. They are literally gold mines. Eros is estimated to hold 40 trillion dollars worth of precious material.<br>
My argument for using nuclear power is 3 fold. Firstly it's the only serious option for manned missions to deep space. Chemical is inadequate and unreliable. The cost would be prohibitive and payload too small. Too much margin for error. Nuclear power is simply more practical. Secondly, Uranium doesn't just exist on Earth. It's already in space and we should use it. Not let it sit there doing nothing. Thirdly, as John has wisely pointed out at other boards, the threat of atomic weapons pales into insignificance compared to the kinetic energy of a rock or spacecraft. Anyone with space access can drop a sizable object on us and effectively wipe out entire cities and continents. Atomic power is inconsequential. Does this mean we should ban spaceflight? Ofcourse not. It simply means we should have a space military to defend us.  <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
<br>Nuclear power is the next logical step for serious space travel. The technology required to colonise the solar system exists now!

<br><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace">NUCLEARSPACE</a>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ualbwartist.showPublicProfile?language=EN>AlBwartist</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/20/02 6:57:15 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=87.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: to the king or queen?</span><hr size=1> Thankyou and to John as well, for all of this information.<br>
<br>
I'd have to say the pronuclear space travel arguments are  quite substantial. Although I think the first item that will be needed is the unifying of goals in the human population.<br>
Whoever finances this type of endeavor will have to open a PR office immediately. Combating political mistrust will be a cash drain on whoever throws money at such an enterprise.<br>
<br>
Every risk  has a  downside and I see the main one as the<br>
mistrust of our neighbor's actions. Even if this is a private<br>
funded enterprise, you still will need the global support for the effort. This will take a rigorous campaign putting forth honorable intentions. A huge expenditure.<br>
<br>
Is there info on what the downside is on these nuclear ideas?<br>
Validation of any effort can only be taken seriously when<br>
the cons are included with the pros. <br>
<br>
Glad I found this forum. Very interesting reading.<br>
<br>
Al<br>
